-- 1. [Problem Restatement] Find all real a satisfying √(4 + √(16 + 16a)) + √(1 + √(1 + a)) = 6. 2. [Key Idea] Notice that 16 + 16a = 16(1 + a); pulling out factors turns both radicals into the same inner expression, allowing a single substitution. 3. [Proof] Let t = √(1 + √(1 + a)) (note a ≥ –1 so t is real). Then √(16 + 16a) = √[16(1 + a)] = 4√(1 + a), 4 + √(16 + 16a) = 4 + 4√(1 + a) = 4(1 + √(1 + a)), √(4 + √(16 + 16a)) = √[4(1 + √(1 + a))] = 2√(1 + √(1 + a)) = 2t. Hence the given equation becomes 2t + t = 6 ⟹ 3t = 6 ⟹ t = 2. Back-substituting, t = √(1 + √(1 + a)) = 2 ⟹ 1 + √(1 + a) = 4 ⟹ √(1 + a) = 3 ⟹ 1 + a = 9 ⟹ a = 8. All steps are reversible and respect a ≥ –1, so a = 8 is the unique solution. 4. [Conclusion] The only real number satisfying the equation is a = 8.
